More consistent behavior around checking for existence of, and removing attributes

- asking for an attribute that does not exist returns an empty string instead of throwing an exception
- setting an attribute to null or empty string removes the attribute
- removing an attribute name "class" removes all CSS classes added via AddClass()
- asking HasAttr("class") will return true if any classes have been added

More consistent behavior around checking for existence of, and removing attributes

- asking for an attribute that does not exist returns an empty string instead of throwing an exception
- setting an attribute to null or empty string removes the attribute
- removing an attribute name "class" removes all CSS classes added via AddClass()
- asking HasAttr("class") will return true if any classes have been added

Decided to keep both Next property and After() method with slightly different behavior.

Next sets and overwrites any existing sibling.
After() sets the next sibling, and any existing sibling will follow the new sibling.
Fixed example in readme.md
Fix bug in DLTag that was adding incorrect HTML for a definition

Cleaning up API in preparation for 1.0 release

- For the 0.9 release, you can still use the methods that are being replaced
  but they are marked with Obsolete tags
- To use Obsolete methods, you must import the HtmlTags.Extended.Compatibility namespace
  to get access to the old method names implemented as extension methods.
  Alternatively, you could copy CompatibilityExtensions.cs to your own project,
  change the namespace to HtmlTags, and remove the Obsolete attributes.
- All members marked Obsolete will be removed for the 1.0 release

Visible() is now Render() - should help differentiate it from Hide(), which renders, but styles with display:none
Child() is now Append() - more consistent with the corresponding jQuery method
Child<T>() is now Add<T>() - consistent with Add() behavior because the child is returned
AddChildren() is now an overload of Append()

Next is now After() - changed to method to allow chaining. Name is consistent with jQuery
EncodeInnerText is now Encoded() - changed to method to allow chaining
UnEncoded() is now an extension method in HtmlTags.Extended.Attributes. Can use Encoded(false) instead.

Many higher-level extension methods were moved to HtmlTags.Extended.Attributes so that they are not imported by default.
Tag building extension methods were moved to HtmlTags.Extended.TagBuilders for the same reason.

Add(string) and Append(string) now accept '>' as a name delimeter (in addition to the original '/'), to be consistent with jQuery

Allow Attr to set class attribute as well

The Attr method will now let you set the class of a tag. It also lets
you set multiple classes when passed in as a space separated string.
This also makes working with Spark bindings much easier as it can be used to
get all the remaining attributes and passed directly to Attr instead of
having to iterate over the attributes and conditionally use the AddClass
or AdClasses methods.
